election_record.label: New York 1812 State Senate, Western District

overview.note: The New-York Herald (New York, NY), The Western Federalist (Auburn, NY), Utica Patriot (Utica, NY), Commercial Advertiser (New York, NY), and New-York Spectator (New York, NY) refer to Archibald S. Clarke, Henry Hager, Russell Atwater, and Francis A. Bloodgood as Democratic candidates.
The New-York Herald (New York, NY), May 27, uses the spelling Hagar for Henry Hager, and uses the name Brunton for Ethel Bronson.
The New-York Spectator (New York, NY), May 30, uses the spelling Hagar for Henry Hager, and the spelling Brunson for Ethel Bronson.
The Columbian, June 15, uses the spelling Russel for Russell Atwater.
The New-York Herald (New York, NY), New-York Spectator (New York, NY), Utica Patriot (Utica, NY), and Commercial Advertiser (New York, NY) refer to the Republican candidates as Democratic.
Perley Keyes, Moss Kent, Peter B. Porter, Myron Holley, and Elijah Miller were were candidates for U.S. House of Representatives.

Thomas Ludlow, William Satterlee, William C. Bennett, Nathaniel Medbury, Ebenezer Wakely, Thornton Wasson, John Graves, Rudolph J. Shoemaker, Hosea Nelson, Hosea Wilson, Rudolph Devendorff, Thomas Manley, Selah Holcomb, Egbert Ten Eyck, Clark Allen, Samuel C. Kanady, Paul Hutchinson, Nehemiah Huntington, Jonathan Olmstead, John D. Henry, Israel Stoddard, Moses Nash, Joshua Forman, Jonathan Stanley, Jr., Herman Hickock, Peter A. Hilton, Abraham Dox and Roger Sprague were candidates for Assembly.
The New-York Herald (New York, NY), May 23, and The Western Federalist (Auburn, NY), May 23, refer to Thomas Ludlow, William Satterlee, and William C. Bennett as Spencerite candidates.
